Introduction¶

Dataset Discription:¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

Dataset Source: Medical Appointment No Shows

</a>

Dataset Dictionary:¶

Column Description
PatientId Identification of a patient
AppointmentID dentification of each appointment
Gender Male or Female . Female is the greater proportion, woman takes way more care of they health in comparison to man.
DataMarcacaoConsulta The day of the actuall appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.
DataAgendamento The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course.
Age How old is the patient.
Neighbourhood indicates the location of the hospital, Where the appointment takes place.
Scholarship indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.
Hipertension indicates whether or not the patient is experiencing Hypertension. True or False
Diabetes indicates whether or not the patient is experiencing Diabetes. True or False
Alcoholism indicates whether or not the patient is experiencing Alcoholism. True or False
Handcap indicates whether or not the patient is with special needs. True or False
SMS_received indicates whether or not the patient has received a reminder text message. 1 or more messages sent to the patient.
No-show No if the patient showed up to their appointment, and Yes if they did not show up.

Questions we are trying to answer :¶

Q1- what is the overall appointment show-up and no show-up rate?

Q2- what are the most feature that affect to No_show?

Description of the analysis¶

first i will find percentage of showed patients and i will find the relations between No_show column and other columns to find Highest Impact Column

note that i will not use (PatientId, AppointmentID, ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay) columns at this analyse but i will check them

General Exploration Results¶

  • The proportion of females is greater than that of males.
  • The Age range is contain nearly all ages (from 0 to 115) and the majority is in very young age and between 20 and 55.
  • There is 81 neighbourhood where the appointment takes place.
  • Most of the patients have No : Scholarship , Hipertension, Diabetes , Alcoholism, Handcap
  • 20% of patient missed their appointment.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

After explore Data let's answer two Questions i found interesting

The main goal is to find what factor has the most affect to number of shows so i will figure the relation between showed patients and factors

Q1 what is the overall appointment show-up and no show-up rate??¶

In [36]:
# making masks to use later
miss = df["No_show"] == "Yes"
show = df["No_show"] == "No"
df['show'] = show
df['miss'] = miss

In [50]:
# function to find the mean and barplot figure
def mean_and_barplot(col):
    print(df.groupby(col)['show'].mean())
    df.groupby(col)['show'].mean().plot(kind='bar',figsize=(22,10));
    plt.xlabel("Show")
    plt.ylabel(col)
    plt.title("relation between"+" "+col+" "+"and patients who showed")
    plt.legend();

all figures below will tell us that if (Hipertension, Handcap, Diabetes, Neighbourhood, Scholarship, SMS_received, Alcoholism and Gender ) taken into account if we want to know the patient will appear at his appointment or not

Conclusions¶

After investigated the correlation between some of the characteristics of the patients and whether they missed or showed to their appointment. And these are the results of these analyses:

  • 20% of the patients didn't go to Medical Appointment
  • Age is the most important factor that decided if a patient would come or not
  • patients from 12 to mid-30s are more likely to miss their appointments
  • Receiving an SMS did not increase the chance that the patient would show to their appointment.
  • most of people who has Scholarship are most likely to miss thier appointments with a percentage of 76.2% of showing and patients who don't have a scholarship have the percentage 80.1%

limitations¶

  • There was no explanation of how the data was collected, and if it was collected in a way that makes these analyses more reliable.
  • The Handcap and SMS_received columns weren't explained clearly on the dataset page.
  • The dataset didn't explain why the patient comes to the doctor, which may give an additional explanation about why they miss their appointments.
  • The PatientId column was little bit confusing
